Stanley Rachman (born 1934) is a psychologist and is Professor Emeritus of the Department of Psychology at the University of British Columbia in Vancouver, Canada.[1] Professor Stanley Jack Rachman is a recognized leader[2][3][4] in the research and treatment of obsessive-compulsive disorder (OCD) and other anxiety disorders and remains highly active in both the research and treatment of OCD. His many contributions and achievements have been recognized by several awards.[5] Professor Rachman serves on multiple editorial boards and was Editor in Chief of Behaviour Research and Therapy for many years until his retirement. He remains a Consulting Editor to this academic journal. He has published many books and hundreds of articles on obsessive-compulsive disorder and other anxiety disorders, recently proposing new cognitive models of and treatments for obsessions and compulsive checking, as well as proposing a revised conceptualization of the fear of contamination. Present position Emeritus Professor of Psychology Institute of Psychiatry, London SE5 8AF. Recipient of British Psychological Society Lifetime Professional Award for 2010. M: PSO/PSI mepr dsrd (o, p, m, p, a, d, s), sysi/epon, spvo proc(eval/thrp), drug(N5A/5B/5C/6A/6B/6D)
